Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Ecobank Ghana, Kenya Airways, Zenith

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-05-03T16:16:49Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-03/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-kenya-airways-zenith-bank-gain.html
The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite
Index advanced for a sixth day, rising 1.4 percent to 1,115.79
at the 3 p.m. close in Accra, the longest rally since Jan. 31.  Namibia’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  fell 1.7 percent to
862.79 by the 4 p.m. close in Windhoek, the lowest since April
19. Kenya’s All-Share Index rose for a second day, gaining 0.2
percent to 75.49 by the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi, the highest
since March 7. Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index added 0.2 percent to
2,065.97 by the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis . The  Nigerian
Stock Exchange  All-Share Index added 0.2 percent to 25,085.59 by
the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according to a statement on the
bourse’s website.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Ecobank Ghana Ltd. (EBG GN), the nation’s third-biggest
lender by market capitalization, gained 3 pesewas, or 0.9
percent, to 3.51 cedis, the most since March 9, after the
company said net income in the three months through March rose
62 percent, to 19.4 million cedis ($13 million), according to a
statement published in Accra-based Daily Graphic newspaper on
April 29.  Kenya Airways Ltd. (KNAL)  , sub-Saharan Africa’s third-
largest airline, rose 1.25 shillings, or 3.5 percent, to 37.25
shillings, the strongest close since April 18. The company
increased its seat-kilometer capacity by 12.5 percent in the
three months to March 31 compared with a year earlier, it said
after the market closed on April 29.  Zenith Bank Plc (ZENITHBA)  ,  Nigeria ’s second-biggest
lender by market value, added 30 kobo, or 2 percent, to 15.30
naira, snapping two days of losses, after profit increased to
15.07 billion naira ($97.3 million) in the three months through
March, it said in a statement on the website of the Nigerian
Stock Exchange dated April 28. The market was closed for a
public holiday yesterday.  Zenith “offers an attraction to value investors,” Vetiva
Capital Management Ltd. said in an e-mailed note to clients
today. The Lagos-based company maintained a “buy” rating on
the stock and its price estimate of 20.24 naira a share,
implying a 35 percent return this year.  To contact the reporter on this story:
